# ============================================================================
# CURSOR AI EXECUTION RULES & PROJECT CONTEXT
# ============================================================================

## AUTONOMY & QUOTA OPTIMIZATION (CRITICAL)
- DO NOT stop to ask clarification questions, permission, or architectural opinions.
- If requirements are ambiguous or missing, make the most logical, industry-standard engineering assumption and proceed immediately with execution.
- If technical choices must be made (e.g., choice of library, design pattern, or utility function), pick the most stable, scalable, and modern option.
- Document all assumptions, architectural choices, and deviations clearly using inline code comments or markdown blocks in your response.

## CODE STYLE & ARCHITECTURE
- Write clean, modular, and maintainable code adhering to SOLID principles.
- Use explicit, descriptive variable and function names; avoid cryptic abbreviations.
- Favor declarative, functional programming patterns (e.g., map, filter, reduce) over imperative loops where appropriate.
- Maintain consistent formatting: use strict linting rules, proper indentation, and clear separation of concerns.
- Avoid code duplication. Refactor existing code into reusable utilities or components if you notice repetitive patterns.
- Keep functions small, focused, and limited to a single responsibility.

## ERROR HANDLING & RESILIENCE
- Never write "silent fail" or empty catch blocks (`catch (e) {}`).
- Every risky operation (I/O, API calls, data parsing) must be wrapped in explicit try/catch blocks or robust error-handling wrappers.
- Provide meaningful, actionable error messages. Log errors with sufficient context to simplify debugging.
- Implement graceful degradation or safe fallback mechanisms so the application does not crash when an edge-case error occurs.
- Validate all incoming data, API payloads, and function inputs before processing them.

## EXECUTION STEP-BY-STEP
1. Read the user's request and analyze the existing codebase context.
2. Formulate the optimal execution plan based on the rules above.
3. Execute all necessary file creations, edits, and terminal commands autonomously.
4. Verify that the changes do not break existing functionality or introduce regressions.
